# Mitosis

Mitosis is how a eukaryotic cell divides its replicated nucleus so each
daughter cell gets an identical copy of the DNA. It has five main phases —
remember the mnemonic **IPMAT** (plus cytokinesis): **I**nterphase,
**P**rophase, **M**etaphase, **A**naphase, **T**elophase.

```text
1. Interphase (preparation)
     • DNA replicates — each chromosome becomes two "sister chromatids"
       joined at a centromere.
     • Cell grows and makes proteins.

2. Prophase
     • Chromatin condenses into visible chromosomes.
     • Nuclear envelope breaks down.
     • Mitotic spindle (microtubules) begins to form from the centrosomes.

3. Metaphase
     • Chromosomes align along the cell's equator ("metaphase plate").
     • Spindle fibers attach to each centromere from opposite poles.

4. Anaphase
     • Sister chromatids separate — centromeres split.
     • Each half moves toward an opposite pole, pulled by spindle fibers.

5. Telophase
     • Nuclear envelopes reform around the two sets of chromosomes.
     • Chromosomes de-condense back into chromatin.

6. Cytokinesis (often shown alongside telophase)
     • Cytoplasm pinches in two. Two daughter cells result, each genetically
       identical to the parent.
```

